column169: During an inspection in the Gallup yard, the FRA inspector found SHQX 7254 leaking and producing a white crystallization of the ammonium nitrate liquid around the bottom outlet valve. Operations Supervisor I Mike Husby contacted safety to report a Hazardous Spill. Mike stated that forklift operator Michael Campbell was removing a pallet from trailer 86161 that was stacked on top of a pallet containing bags of UN3378, Sodium carbonate peroxyhydrate, 5.1, PG II. Mike stated that wo oden pallet had punctured through the cardboard dunnage that was placed between the two pallets. Mike stated that when forklift operator Michael Campbell lifted pallet on top the pallet had snagged one of the bags of UN3378 and when he started to back up it pulled one of the bags out of the shrink w rap. Mike stated that the bag ripped resulting in a spillage of 40-lbs of UN3378 onto the trailer floor.

column43: LITHIUM ION BATTERIES INCLUDING LITHIUM ION POLYMER BATTERIES
column169: DURING THE PRE-LOAD OPERATIONS AT THE UPS UTRECHT FACILITY IN THE NETHERLANDS ONE PACKAGE FELT WARM TO THE TOUCH AND SHOWED SIGNS OF SMOKE. THE PACKAGE WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED FROM THE BUILDING AND SECURED.  THERE WERE NO VISIBLE FLAMES OBSERVED. DURING INNER CONTENT INSPECTION THERE IS EVIDENCE OF BURNING, MELTING, AND CHARRING OF THE INNER CONTENTS. THE INCIDENT PACKAGE WAS MARKED AND LABELLED AS UN3480, LITHIUM ION BATTERIES, SECTION IA OF PACKING INSTRUCTION 965 WITH A CARGO AIRCRAFT ONLY AND CLASS 9 LITHIUM BATTERY LABEL. THE PACKAGE WAS PART OF A THREE PACKAGE SHIPMENT WITH AN APPROPRIATE IATA SHIPPERS DECLARATION AND HAD PASSED AN ACCEPTANCE AUDIT IN HONG KONG ON 15-NOV-2024. THE PACKAGE HAD PREVIOUSLY FLOWN ON UPS AIRCRAFT FROM HKG - SHJ - CGN BEFORE EXPERIENCING THE THERMAL EVENT IN UTRECHT, NETHERLANDS. THERE ARE TWO ADDITIONAL PACKAGES IN THE SHIPMENT THAT WERE ALSO REMOVED AND SECURED, TRACKING NUMBERS 1Z802E150499401436 AND 1Z802E150495846446. THESE TWO PACKAGES WERE NOT INVOLVED IN THE LITHIUM BATTERY EVENT. THE PACKAGE WAS REPORTED TO THE NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER ON 04-DEC-2024, REPORT NUMBER 1417932.

column170: Instruct dock crews to inspect hazardous materials freight as it is moved on and off trailers to ensure spills are discovered and cleaned quickly.

column169: XPO Logistics terminal XNW experienced a UN2920 Dicoco Dimethyl Ammonium Chloride release from a 330-gallon poly tote. ERTS dispatched contractors to conduct cleanup operations. The tote was then decontaminated, wiped down, and secured for continued shipment on. The impacted pads used to clean the tote were containerized into a 5-gallon poly drum. The waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.
